				</table>
			
							When a ranger issues you printed instructions that tell you to set up your tent within 15 feet of the stake that marks a campsite, you damn well better.  I went backpacking in <a target="_blank" href="http://www.nps.gov/romo/visit/index.html" title="Rocky Mountain National Park">Rocky Mountain National Park</a> this weekend, and returned from a hike to Lake Nanita to find our tent had been ticketed.  Weâ€™d set it up outside of the 15-foot radius, and apparently there are rangers tramping through the backcountry carrying rulers during the day to punish all rule-breakers.  <br />
<br />
The ranger seemed a little miffed; in addition to the official ticket, he left a handwritten note admonishing us to â€œ<u>move</u> your tentâ€? and â€œpick up your campsite when you leave.â€? As if we werenâ€™t going to!  Though our tent actions look shady, weâ€™re not that kind of campers, really! I noticed that the ranger had also destroyed a renegade campfire site that was set up by a previous camperâ€”he probably thought weâ€™d done that, too.  <br />
<br />
The ticket was for $25â€”a minor nuisance, but a little demoralizing because of the scolding he gave us.  I was happy to give $25 to the cause of sustaining such a wonderful national park, but suspiciously, we had to mail our fine to some government office in Georgia.  I hope the fine will benefit Rocky Mountain National Park, but it will probably go toward funding some unscrupulous senatorâ€™s pork barrel project. Live and learn: Next time youâ€™re backpacking in Rocky Mountain National Park, be sure to pack in a yard stick.
						<b>[End of article]</b>
