		<!-- Begin Comments -->
		
		<b>Comment By Jim Mackay, 8-25-05</b>
		<p>Jenny I had a similar experience this summer in Yellowstone.  All I wanted to do was float with my kids down a section of the river, not knowing this was against the rules. I took a pretty good dressing down from a volunteer, not even a real ranger.<br />
<br />
In their defense, after describing this incident to a friend of mine who is a ranger in Rocky Mountain National Park, he explained that the parks are under a huge amount of stress, including a $4.6 billion dollar backlog in maintenance (see <a href="http://www.newwest.net/?URL=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.coloradocollege.edu%2Fstateoftherockies%2F05ReportCard%2FNational_Parks.pdf">http://www.coloradocollege.edu/stateoftherockies/05ReportCard/National_Parks.pdf</a>).  And the number of visitors keeps on growing.  In response, the park service has taken somewhat draconian measures to ensure that the strict rules are followed, no exceptions.  In fact they won't even engage in a discussion about the rules - the standard answer from everyone I challenged about a rule was "I don't make the rules, I just enforce them".<br />
<br />
Our best bet is to continue as an indivivuals to buy our annual Parks pass, and to lobby for more funding.  Better yet, frequent the State parks in the Rocky Mountains, which are beautiful and a little less strict due to the lower visitor numbers.</p>
		
		<b>Comment By Zach, 8-28-05</b>
		<p>For what it's worth, as a former ranger (although not in law enforcement), I don't really see anything wrong w/ what he did in issuing you a ticket. Unfortunately there are a lot of backcountry idiots out there who will break every rule in the book and, as a result, end up not only severely impacting the backcountry, but also ruining other's experiences in the process. The individual ranger who issued your ticket had no way of knowing whether you were one of those individuals (nor do I). As such, I'd say it's better to err on the side of resource protection. And unfortunately that's exactly how we have to manage our public lands: for the lowest common human denominator.</p>
		
